<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,541,1287]" box="[199,657,649,676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">
Adult (
<figureCitation box="[278,348,649,675]" captionStart="FIGURES 1‒4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1301,1325]" captionTargetBox="[166,1418,366,1269]" captionTargetId="figure-104@2.[151,1435,345,1277]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1‒4. Adults of Lepidozonates spp. (all dorsal view). 1. L. adusta comb. nov., ♀; 2. L. prominens, ♂; 3. L. semiovatus sp. nov., holotype, ♂; 4. L. tenebrosellus, ♀. Scales = 2.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4431497" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4431497/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 18.0–21.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,541,1287]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">
<emphasis box="[199,391,685,711]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[407,492,685,711]" captionStart="FIGURES 12‒14" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[215,1371,181,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[205,1382,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12‒14. Female genitalia of Lepidozonates spp. 12. L. adusta comb. nov., slide No. YS20192; 13. L. semiovatus sp. nov., paratype, slide No. YS20198; 13a. enlarged ductus seminalis; 14. L. tenebrosellus, slide No. YS20193; 14a. enlarged ductus seminalis. Scales = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4431505" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4431505/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Apophyses posteriores about 1.5 times length of apophyses anteriores; apophyses anteriores with a small ramification at basal 1/3. Antrum membranous except posterior margin sclerotized and roundly produced medially. Ductus bursae slightly longer than twice length of corpus bursae, twisted anteriorly, weakly sclerotized in posterior 1/5, membranous in anterior 4/5, dilated at posterior 1/4, with dense spines posteriorly and sparse spines medially; ductus seminalis slender, arising from about posterior 2/5 of ductus bursae, with dense denticles on inner wall (
<figureCitation box="[486,581,865,891]" captionStart="FIGURES 12‒14" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[215,1371,181,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[205,1382,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12‒14. Female genitalia of Lepidozonates spp. 12. L. adusta comb. nov., slide No. YS20192; 13. L. semiovatus sp. nov., paratype, slide No. YS20198; 13a. enlarged ductus seminalis; 14. L. tenebrosellus, slide No. YS20193; 14a. enlarged ductus seminalis. Scales = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4431505" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4431505/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">Fig. 14a</figureCitation>
). Corpus bursae elliptical, granulose; signum rounded, serrate along margins, with a rectangular, denticulate median groove.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,541,1287]" box="[199,1139,937,964]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">
<emphasis box="[199,305,937,963]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Female eighth abdominal sternite concave at middle on posterior margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="597" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,541,1287]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,973,999]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Park" authorityYear="2018" box="[621,733,973,999]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Lepidozonates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="landryi">
<emphasis box="[621,733,973,999]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">L. landryi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it can be distinguished by the black forewing, and in the male genitalia by the flap from the dorsal surface of the juxta shorter than the juxta, and the aedeagus as long as the valva (
<figureCitation box="[270,352,1045,1071]" captionStart="FIGURES 8‒11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1980,2004]" captionTargetBox="[163,1428,961,1947]" captionTargetId="figure-398@4.[151,1435,957,1957]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8‒11. Male genitalia of Lepidozonates spp. 8. L. adusta comb. nov., slide No. YS20195; 9. L. prominens, slide No. YS20210; 10. L. semiovatus sp. nov., holotype, slide No. YS20194; 11. L. tenebrosellus, slide No. YS20141. Scales = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4431503" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4431503/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); in the latter species, the forewing is yellowish brown, the flap is longer than the juxta, and the aedeagus is shorter than the valva. It is also similar to the new species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Yu &amp; Wang, 2021" authorityName="Yu &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2021" box="[956,1110,1082,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Lepidozonates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semiovatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[956,1110,1082,1107]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">L. semiovatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1118,1208,1081,1107]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1118,1208,1081,1107]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, and the differences between them are stated in the diagnosis of the latter species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
